				<h1 class="content_headers">Taormina, Italy</h1>
				<article  id="article">
					<img src="/sites/worldtour/public/img/mount_etna.jpg" alt="Mount Etna" id="etna"> 
					What do Goethe, Alexander Dumas, Johannes Brahms, Gustav Klimt, D.H. Lawrence, Richard Wagner, Oscar Wilde, Truman Capote, John Steinbeck, Ingmar Bergmann, Francis Ford Coppola, Leonard Bergman, Marlene Dietrich, Greta Garbo, Federico Fellini, Cary Grant, Gregory Peck, Elisabeth Taylor and Woody Allen have in common? Simple - they have all sojourned in Taormina, the pearl of the Mediterranean. <span class="rmore">[Read more...]</span><br/><br/>
					<div class="article_more">
						<article id="hidden_article">
							Taormina is centred around its main thoroughfare, Corso Umberto I. At the beginning of this charming street is perhaps the greatest symbol of Taormina’s long varied history: Palazzo Corvaja. Its architecture is a sublime mix of Arab, Norman and Gothic and includes battlements, mullioned windows and shady courtyards. The Arabs built the original tower as part of the town’s defences. Its cubic structure, which is typical of many Arab towers of this period, is thought to have evoked that of the Ka’aba in Mecca. In the 13th Century the tower was enlarged by the Normans who added a wing containing a hall and some wonderful artwork. The Spanish followed suit, adding another wing at the beginning of the 15th Century to house the Sicilian Parliament. Its present name recalls one of the town’s most important noble families who owned the building from 1538 to 1945.<br/><br/>
							For the first half of the 20th Century, until after the 2nd World War, Palazzo Corvaja became a kind of lodging house for poor families and fell into disrepair. After the war it was restored to its former glory and in 1960 another section was added to house the local tourism offices. The main part now houses the Sicilian Museum of Art and Popular Traditions.<br/><br/>
							At the other end of Corso Umberto I is Piazza del Duomo, complete with 13th Century Cathedral and Baroque fountain. As with many churches of this period in Sicily, the Duomo, dedicated to Saint Nicholas of Bari, has a distinctly fortress-like quality thanks to its robust structure and the battlements that delineate the roof. Its Renaissance doorway belies an essentially Gothic interior complete with a rose window at the west end.<br/><br/>
							Taormina is served by its very own cable car which ferries tourists to and from the seaside resorts down along the coast. Extensive beaches, rocky coves, tiny islands (such as the famous Isola Bella) and sea stacks abound, making this enchanting coastline a firm favourite with Sicilians and visitors alike. <span class="vless">[View less...]</span> <br/><br/>
						</article>
						<article>
							<h3>Places to see</h3>
							For a real taste of Sicily try a Sunday morning in Castelbuono, south of Cefalù; think Sicilian Ludlow. The shops move outside and tastings are obligatory. An eclectic mix of sausages and salamis, preserves and chocolates, amazing biscuits and cakes, gelato in a multitude of flavours and panettone – so many types – and delectable spreads (try the smooth “cream of almond” on freshly baked panettone, so light it almost floats away).
							This is not a tourist attraction, so be prepared to jostle with the local children who are on the front row for tastings, then have a break from free samples and sit in the square to enjoy an espresso, the church bells and a spot of people watching. Heavenly.<br/><br/>
							<h3>Atmospheric amphitheatres</h3>
							Starting from Catania, you could make Siracusa, with its beautiful medieval buildings and Greek amphitheatre, your first stop. Try the fish restaurants before heading for Agrigento, with its classical temples. Continue to unmissable Segesta and, perhaps, Selinunte; both wind-swept classical temple sites. Stay on the coast at Castellammare del Golfo, where pastel-painted houses tumble down to the harbour (fish baked in salt is memorable here); farther along there's pretty Cefalù.
							Busy Palermo is worth a visit, then head up into the mountains to Castelbuono to see real, old atmospheric Sicily, before driving on to stay near Taormina. Here, visit the spectacular amphitheatre – but make sure you go early.<br/><br/>
							<h3>Make your own way around</h3>
							We stayed at the Costa Azul hotel, a small modern hotel close to the beach on the Gulf of Castellammare, and an energetic walk from Balestrate (beware of stray dogs and broken glass and litter on the sand). We hired a taxi rather than going on trips organised by the hotel, which was cheaper and more convenient.
							We recommend stopping at Antica Pasticceria del Convento (Via Vittorio Emanuele II 14), a pastry shop in the medieval fortress town of Erice; visiting Trapani, the old town, which is architecturally stunning with its quaint squares; taking a guided tour of a Marsala wine distillery; and not missing the windmills at Infersa salt pans.<br/><br/>
							<h3>Siracusa's war graves</h3>
							Fascinating as Siracusa's ancient ruins are, our lasting memory is of the Commonwealth World War Two cemetery, where young men who died in the 1943 landings lie under rows of white headstones in trimmed green grass. Sobering in the heat.<br/><br/>
